<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-what-is-an-argument">

  <title>What Is an Argument?</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-arguments-intro">
    <p>
      Spend ten minutes listening in any public space and you will notice
      people doing all sorts of things with language. They are telling
      stories, ordering food, complaining about traffic, complimenting
      each other's shoes, explaining how the parking app works, confessing
      crushes, lying about their weekends, asking for directions, and,
      even, on occasion, trying to convince someone of something using
      actual reasons.
    </p>
    <p>
      That last activity, the giving-reasons one, is what we'll call
      <term>making an argument</term>, and it is the subject of this book.
      The other activities are largely where we find and make meaning with
      each other, but arguments are special in their own way as well.
      Arguments let us ask: <q>is this any good?</q> You can't ask that of
      <q>good morning</q> or <q>could you pass the salt?</q> You can ask
      it of <q>Since data centers demand immense power, we must expand
      the electrical grid,</q> and the answer is not obvious until you
      stop and look closely (and might not be obvious even then).
    </p>
    <p>
      This book is about how to look closely.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-language">
    <title>What We Do With Language</title>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-catalog">
      <title>A short list of things we do with language</title>
      <p>
        Take all the things people do with language — every overheard
        sentence, every text, every email — and you can sort them, loosely,
        into a handful of types. The list isn't exact; many sentences do
        more than one thing at once, and philosophers of language have
        argued for a long time about exactly how the categories work. But
        for our purposes, a working list looks something like this.
      </p>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Stating</title>
          <p>
            <q>It's raining.</q> <q>The library closes at nine.</q>
            <q>Data centers consume a lot of power.</q> Statements assert
            that something is the case. They can be true or false, and
            that is the property we are going to care about most.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Asking</title>
          <p>
            <q>What time is it?</q> <q>Did you eat already?</q> Questions
            request information. They aren't true or false themselves,
            even though their answers might be.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Commanding</title>
          <p>
            <q>Close the door.</q> <q>Show your ID.</q> Commands and
            requests try to get someone to do something. They're not
            true or false either, though there are good and bad ones.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Promising</title>
          <p>
            <q>I'll be there by seven.</q> <q>We'll consider your
            application by the fifteenth.</q> A promise commits the
            speaker to some future action. It's evaluable in its own
            way — promises are kept or broken — but not as true or false
            at the moment of speaking.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Expressing</title>
          <p>
            <q>Ouch.</q> <q>What a beautiful day.</q> Expressions report
            or perform an inner state. They're sincere or insincere,
            fitting or off-key, but again, not really true or false.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Performing</title>
          <p>
            Some sentences make something happen just by being said in
            the right circumstances. <q>I now pronounce you married.</q>
            <q>I name this ship the <em>Enterprise</em>.</q>
            <q>I apologize.</q> The philosopher J. L. Austin called these
            <term>performative</term> sentences and noticed they're a
            strange beast: they don't describe a marriage, a naming, or
            an apology — the act of uttering the right phrase under the
            right circumstances is just what it is to do the thing.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Greeting</title>
          <p>
            <q>Good morning.</q> <q>Hey.</q> <q>How's it going?</q> A
            great deal of human conversation is just acknowledging that
            other humans exist and are not strangers. The semantic
            content of <q>How's it going?</q> is roughly zero. The social
            work it does is enormous.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Explaining</title>
          <p>
            <q>The reason your phone is hot is that you've been on it
            for two hours.</q> <q>I'm late because there was an accident
            on Route 17.</q> Explanations look a lot like arguments —
            they offer reasons connected to a claim — and we'll come
            back to that resemblance later. For now just note that this
            distinction is a little tricky, but we'll want to pay
            attention to it.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Arguing</title>
          <p>
            <q>You shouldn't take Route 17 — there was an accident, and
            traffic is backed up to the next exit.</q> <q>We need to
            expand the grid because data centers are coming online faster
            than we can power them.</q> An argument offers reasons in
            support of a claim. The reasons are called <term>premises</term>,
            the supported claim is called the <term>conclusion</term>,
            and the relationship between them is mostly what the rest of
            this book is about.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-two-senses">
      <title>Two senses of <q>argument</q></title>
      <!--
        STYLE NOTE: Reno's revision uses italics-only for word-mentions
        of "argument", "argue", "arguing" here. This contrasts with the
        quotes+italics pattern used for "valid" and "sound" in the
        "What makes an argument good?" subsection below. We're keeping
        Reno's pattern as written; convention to be confirmed.
      -->
      <p>
        The word <em>argument</em> and its related verb forms
        <em>argue</em>, <em>arguing</em> are ambiguous in everyday
        English. They often refer to a verbal disagreement — two people
        exchanging insults, or yelling at each other about whether the
        runner was safe: <q>He was out!</q> <q>No way! He was safe!</q>
        That kind of dispute is not what we'll mean by <em>argument</em>
        in this book. We'll be using the word in the more specialized
        sense from the catalog above: an offering of reasons in support
        of a claim. From here on, when you see <em>argument</em>, that's
        the meaning to assume.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-persuading">
      <title>Persuading and arguing</title>
      <p>
        One thing you might notice in the list above is that I haven't
        said anything about <em>persuading</em>. That's deliberate.
        Persuasion isn't really a separate category — it's something a
        person can be trying to do across many of the categories at once.
        Importantly, you can persuade someone without arguing.
      </p>
      <p>
        Advertising is the cleanest example. Most ads don't make
        arguments. They show you a beautiful person enjoying a beautiful
        product in beautiful light, and they hope that you, watching,
        will associate the product with the feeling of beauty. There's
        no premise, no conclusion, no reasoning offered. There's just an
        emotional pairing. If you walk away from the ad wanting the
        product, the ad has succeeded — but it did not argue.
      </p>
      <p>
        Politicians do this too. So do friends, parents, salespeople,
        professors, and AI chatbots. A great deal of persuasion happens
        through repetition, charm, fear, social pressure, identity, and
        the sheer confidence with which a claim is delivered. None of
        this is arguing. None of it requires reasons.
      </p>
      <p>
        The reverse is also true. You can make a careful, airtight
        argument and persuade exactly nobody. Anyone who has tried to
        talk an unwilling family member out of a strongly held belief
        knows the experience.
      </p>
      <p>
        Logic is about the <em>reasoning</em> embedded in argumentative
        language, not about whether the reasoning works on its audience.
        Whether arguments persuade is, much of the time, a question of
        human psychology, and humans are persuaded by all sorts of things
        that have nothing to do with reasons. Whether arguments are
        <em>good</em> is a different question — a logical question — and
        it is the one we will spend the rest of this book learning to
        answer.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-good-argument">
      <title>What makes an argument good?</title>
      <p>
        The central observation of the opening was that arguments are
        the kind of language use about which we can ask, <q>is this any
        good?</q> You can ask other questions of other kinds of speech:
        whether a promise was kept, whether a question was relevant,
        whether an explanation was satisfying, whether a greeting was
        warm. But <q>is this argument any good?</q> is a question that
        implies a specific structure, and the structure implied by that
        question is what the rest of the book is for.
      </p>
      <p>
        What does it actually mean for an argument to be good?
      </p>
      <p>
        A first answer: a good argument is one whose conclusion really
        does follow from its premises. If the premises support the
        conclusion, then accepting the premises gives you reason to
        accept the conclusion. If the premises do not support the
        conclusion, the argument is bad — even if every sentence in it
        happens to be true. Bad reasoning can land on a true conclusion
        by accident; good reasoning can sometimes land on a false
        conclusion if the premises were false. Both happen all the time.
        This is because a good argument isn't just about truth and
        falsity.
      </p>
      <p>
        Logicians have a specific vocabulary for these properties. The
        word <q><term>valid</term></q> means roughly <q>the conclusion
        really does follow from the premises,</q> and it applies to the
        structure of an argument, not its content. And the word
        <q><term>sound</term></q> means <q>valid, and all the premises
        are also actually true.</q> For now, treat those as labels; we
        will fill in their precise meanings in the next chapter.
        <!--
          TODO: Reno, this sentence in your revision ends mid-thought:
          "those are the questions you can ask of an argument and not
          of sentences like 'good morning' or"
          Pasting a placeholder completion below; replace with what you
          actually want.
        -->
        The point is that those are the questions you can ask of an
        argument and not of sentences like <q>good morning</q> or
        <q>close the door.</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-two-kinds">
      <title>Two kinds of arguing</title>
      <p>
        Arguments come in two broad kinds, and we'll discuss both in
        this book.
      </p>
      <p>
        Some arguments are <term>deductive</term>. In a deductive
        argument, the premises are supposed to guarantee the conclusion.
        A deductive argument asserts that if the premises are true, the
        conclusion has to be true too, no exceptions. If it's valid, and
        sound, then it works; it's a good argument. <q>All humans are
        mortal. Socrates is human. Therefore Socrates is mortal.</q> If
        you accept the premises, you can't dodge the conclusion without
        contradicting yourself. Most of Parts I, II, and III of this book
        are about deductive reasoning.
      </p>
      <p>
        Other arguments are <term>inductive</term>. In an inductive
        argument, the premises don't guarantee the conclusion, but they
        make it more likely than it would have been otherwise. Here's a
        <term>strong</term> inductive argument: <q>The last hundred
        flamingos I saw were pink. So the next flamingo I see will
        probably be pink too.</q> The conclusion isn't guaranteed even
        if the premises are all true; it's supported. Inductive arguments
        are the workhorses of science, statistics, medicine, and most
        everyday reasoning. Part IV of this book is about inductive
        reasoning, with statistical inference as its centerpiece.
      </p>
      <p>
        Both kinds count as arguing. Both can be done well or badly. The
        standards of <q>good</q> are different in each case — what makes
        a deductive argument good is not the same as what makes an
        inductive one good — but in both cases we can ask the same
        question we asked above: <q>is this argument any good?</q>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        To talk about arguments precisely, we need vocabulary for their
        parts. Arguments are built out of <term>statements</term> —
        claims that are either true or false — combined in particular
        ways. Some statements serve as premises, some as conclusions,
        and in compound arguments some serve as both. Not all sentences
        are statements, though: greetings, questions, and commands
        aren't, as the list above suggests. The next section gets
        specific about what statements are and how to recognize them,
        because we can't say much about arguments without first saying
        what they're made of.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-1-1-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Listen for ten minutes</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a public space — a coffee shop, a hallway between classes,
          a bus stop, a dorm common area — and listen for ten minutes
          without participating. (You can pretend to be on your phone.
          Nobody will notice.)
        </p>
        <p>
          While you listen, try to spot the different kinds of language
          use from the catalog above. You don't have to be exact, and
          many things you hear will fit more than one category at once.
          Notice especially:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              How often you hear someone making an actual argument —
              that is, giving reasons in support of a claim.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Where the arguments tend to appear (between strangers,
              close friends, parents and kids, strangers with strong
              opinions about parking).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Whether anything you heard sounded like an argument but,
              on second thought, was doing a different job — an
              explanation, a complaint, a vent, a recital of grievances.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          You don't have to write any of this down right now. The point
          is just to start noticing the difference. We'll come back to
          it in an end-of-chapter writing prompt, where you'll be asked
          to report and reflect on what you heard.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-statements">
    <title>Statements</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        We can't talk carefully about arguments without being clear about
        what they are built out of. An argument is a structure — one or
        more statements offered in support of another statement — and
        every piece of that structure is a particular kind of sentence.
        Before we can do any actual logic, we need to be clear about what
        statements are and, just as importantly, what they are not.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-what-is-statement">
      <title>What a statement is</title>
      <p>
        A statement is an <term>assertoric</term> sentence — a sentence
        that says something is the case. The word <em>assertoric</em>
        comes from <em>assert</em>; an assertoric sentence is one that
        makes a claim about how things are. Every statement is either
        true or false.
      </p>
      <p>
        That definition is short, and we'll spend the rest of this
        section unpacking what it does and does not mean. But it is
        worth saying directly first.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-statement">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>statement</term> is an assertoric sentence — a
            sentence that says something is the case. Every statement
            is either true or false.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Only sentences in the <em>stating</em> category produce
        assertions. The other categories don't. Questions don't make
        claims about how things are; commands don't either; expressions
        and greetings and performatives are doing other work. None of
        those produce sentences that are true or false.
      </p>
      <p>
        A few examples of statements:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><q>The library closes at nine.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><q>Snow is white.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><q>Carthage was destroyed in 146 BCE.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><q>Two plus two equals four.</q></p></li>
        <li><p><q>Data centers consume a great deal of electricity.</q></p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Each of these sentences claims that something is the case. Each
        is true or false. Most of them are also things almost nobody
        would push back on, and that's deliberate — we're starting with
        the easy cases.
      </p>
      <p>
        A few examples of sentences that are <em>not</em> statements:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><q>What time is it?</q> (a question)</p></li>
        <li><p><q>Close the door.</q> (a command)</p></li>
        <li><p><q>Ouch.</q> (an expression)</p></li>
        <li><p><q>Good morning.</q> (a greeting)</p></li>
        <li><p><q>I now pronounce you married.</q> (a performative)</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        None of these are statements, because none of them say that
        something is the case. None of them is true or false. They are
        doing other things with language, and those other things are
        valuable, but they aren't what arguments are built out of.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-harder-cases">
      <title>What about the harder cases?</title>
      <p>
        So far, so good. The examples above were chosen to be easy:
        nobody is going to fight you about whether the library closes
        at nine. But you may have already started to notice that real
        life isn't always like that. Sentences like <q>there is
        intelligent life somewhere else in the universe,</q> <q>slavery
        is wrong,</q> <q>there were exactly 27,891 people living in
        Fredericksburg in 1856,</q> and <q>the one-millionth digit of
        <m>\pi</m> is 7</q> all <em>seem</em> to be saying that
        something is the case. By the definition above, they should
        all be statements. But they don't feel like the library
        example. Some of them are deeply contested. Others involve
        facts nobody alive knows or can easily find out.
      </p>
      <p>
        Are they still statements?
      </p>
      <p>
        The short answer is yes. The longer answer requires getting
        clear on what is actually being asked. To handle the harder
        cases — the contested ones, the ones we can't easily, if at
        all, verify — we need to separate three things that often get
        smushed together: what is the case, what we <em>know</em>
        about what is the case, and what we <em>agree about</em> about
        what is the case. Once those three are pulled apart, the
        harder cases are no harder to classify than the library
        example.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-truth-knowledge-consensus">
      <title>Truth, knowledge, and consensus are different things</title>
      <p>
        What is the case is one thing. Whether anyone knows what is the
        case is another thing. Whether everyone agrees about what is
        the case is yet a third. These three are easy to run together
        in everyday speech, but they are genuinely separate, and
        statementhood depends only on the first.
      </p>
      <p>
        Consider a few examples in turn.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Things that are true or false even if we don't know which.</alert>
      </p>
      <p>
        There were exactly 27,891 people living in Fredericksburg on
        January 26th, 1856. Nobody alive knows whether that's true.
        The historical record isn't fine-grained enough to settle it.
        The sentence is still either true or false. The population of
        Fredericksburg, VA on January 26th, 1856 is a fact about the
        world; the sentence asserts that the number of people living
        here on that date was 27,891; the sentence is true if that was
        the number and false if it wasn't.
      </p>
      <p>
        There is intelligent life elsewhere in the universe. We don't
        know. We may never know. The sentence is still either true or
        false right now, today, regardless of what humans manage to
        find out in the next century or the next ten thousand years.
      </p>
      <p>
        The one-millionth digit of <m>\pi</m> is 7. Almost nobody has
        computed this. (For what it's worth, it's possible to look up;
        I haven't.) The sentence has a definite truth value at this
        moment, even for those of us who haven't checked.
      </p>
      <p>
        Caesar walked under a particular fig tree on the Ides of March,
        44 BCE. The world has not preserved that information for us.
        We can't recover it. The sentence is still either true or
        false; the world either was or wasn't arranged that way at
        that moment even though we don't know if it was or not.
      </p>
      <p>
        In each of these cases, the sentence is a statement, and for
        the same reason: there is a way the world was, or is, that the
        sentence makes a claim about. Whether <em>we</em> have access
        to that way the world was or is — whether anyone has computed
        it, recovered it from history, observed it, or proven it — is
        a different question. Statementhood depends on the first;
        knowledge is a question on top of it.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Things that are true or false even if we don't agree about which it is.</alert>
      </p>
      <p>
        Now consider a different kind of difficulty. <q>God exists.</q>
        Humans have been arguing about this sentence for as long as
        they've been arguing about anything. We have not settled it.
        The sentence is still either true or false. Whichever it is,
        the disagreement among humans does not change it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The same goes for <q>slavery is wrong,</q> <q>capital punishment
        is unjust,</q> <q>abortion is morally permissible in the first
        trimester,</q> and many other claims people have strong,
        divergent views about. These sentences make claims about how
        things are — about what is moral, what is just, what the world
        contains. Each is either true or false. Whether reasonable
        people agree is a separate question. Whether anyone can settle
        the disagreement is a third question. Neither is the same as
        whether the sentence is a statement. It is.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the part that you might resist even if you buy the rest
        of this discussion. <em>Surely</em> if smart people disagree
        about a sentence, it must be that the sentence isn't really
        true or false — it must be that there's no fact of the matter,
        just a clash of preferences. That's not the assumption of
        classical logic, and it's not the assumption of this book.
        The assumption here is that disagreement and truth are
        different things. People can disagree about what's true.
        People can be wrong about what's true. None of that changes
        whether there's a fact of the matter, neither does it change
        that people are asserting something about the world when they
        utter these sorts of sentences.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Why this matters for what comes later.</alert>
        This isn't a philosophical sidebar. It's load-bearing structure
        for everything in the rest of the book. Truth tables work
        because every row has a definite truth value, regardless of
        what we happen to know about that row. Validity is a
        relationship between truth values. The reasoning we're going
        to teach you depends, all the way down, on the assumption that
        statements are either true or false — no matter who knows
        what, and no matter who agrees with whom.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-fact-vs-opinion">
      <title>The fact-vs-opinion taxonomy doesn't help</title>
      <p>
        Many of you were taught somewhere along the way to sort
        sentences into two bins: <em>facts</em> (which are true and
        provable) and <em>opinions</em> (which are subjective,
        debatable, and somehow not really claims about how things
        are). That taxonomy is not useful for logic. It is, in fact,
        actively in the way. This subsection is about why.
      </p>
      <p>
        Try a quick test on the distinction. Can there be false facts?
      </p>
      <p>
        Most people, asked cold, will say no. <em>Fact</em> in
        ordinary speech already means <q>true claim.</q> That's the
        whole point of saying <q>it's a fact</q> instead of just
        saying the thing. But notice what that concession costs the
        taxonomy. If the word <em>fact</em> already builds truth into
        itself, then <em>fact</em> cannot help us sort sentences
        before we have figured out what is true. The fact-vs-opinion
        taxonomy is asking us to grade the answers before we have
        read the questions.
      </p>
      <p>
        There's a second problem. Even sentences that everyone agrees
        with become <em>opinions</em> the moment somebody asserts
        them. If I say <q>two plus two equals four,</q> that's my
        belief — my opinion about how arithmetic works. It is also a
        fact. The same sentence is in both categories at once,
        depending on how you frame it. The categories don't pick out
        two different kinds of sentences; they collapse into each
        other on contact.
      </p>
      <p>
        A third problem. People sometimes use <em>opinion</em> in a
        looser sense — meaning something like <q>a claim that hasn't
        been settled.</q> On that usage, <em>opinion</em> names not a
        kind of sentence but a feature of how the conversation is
        going. That doesn't help us either. From the perfectly
        settled premises <q>2 + 5 = 7</q> and <q>3 + 4 = 7</q> you
        can build the argument <q>therefore (2 + 5) = (3 + 4).</q>
        It's a boring argument, but unmistakably an argument. Settled
        premises do not make a piece of reasoning stop being
        reasoning. And we already saw above that <em>unsettled</em>
        sentences — <q>God exists,</q> <q>slavery is wrong,</q> and
        the rest — are still statements. Settledness and statementhood
        have nothing to do with each other.
      </p>
      <p>
        So here is the replacement we want.
      </p>
      <principle xml:id="principle-statement-criterion">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The criterion for whether a sentence is a statement is not
            whether it is a <q>fact</q> or an <q>opinion.</q> It is
            whether the sentence is assertoric — whether it says that
            something is the case. If yes, it is a statement; it has
            a truth value; logic can operate on it. If no, it is some
            other kind of speech, and logic operates on it only
            indirectly, if at all.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </principle>
      <p>
        And, looking ahead one section, a related replacement: the
        criterion for whether something is an argument is also not
        whether the statements involved are facts or opinions. It is
        purely structural: some statements offered in support of
        another. We'll get to the details of that structure in the
        next section.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-1-2">
      <title>Where we're headed</title>
      <p>
        Statements are the building blocks. The next section is about
        how those blocks fit together. What is a premise, technically
        speaking? What is a conclusion? What does it mean for one
        statement to support another? Once we have named those parts,
        we can start asking the question that drives the rest of the
        book: what makes one arrangement of statements a good argument
        and another arrangement a bad one. <em>Is this any good?</em>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-1-2-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Sort the sentences</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Below is a list of sentences. For each one, decide whether
          it is a statement (an assertoric sentence — one that says
          something is the case, and is therefore either true or
          false) or not.
        </p>
        <p>
          Use the definition from this section. Do not use the
          fact-vs-opinion taxonomy. Some of these sentences will
          tempt you to mis-sort them as <q>just opinions</q> or
          <q>not really statements.</q> Resist that temptation.
          Trust the definition.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>The library closes at nine.</p></li>
          <li><p>What time does the library close?</p></li>
          <li><p>Slavery is wrong.</p></li>
          <li><p>Pass the salt.</p></li>
          <li><p>There were exactly 27,891 people living in Fredericksburg in 1856.</p></li>
          <li><p>God exists.</p></li>
          <li><p>Chocolate ice cream is better than vanilla.</p></li>
          <li><p>Hey.</p></li>
          <li><p>There is no such thing as a false fact.</p></li>
          <li><p>The one-millionth digit of <m>\pi</m> is 7.</p></li>
          <li><p>We need to expand the electrical grid to keep up with new data centers.</p></li>
          <li><p>Ouch.</p></li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          For at least three of the sentences you sorted as
          statements, write a one-sentence explanation of why someone
          might mistakenly think they are <em>not</em> statements.
          We'll come back to this in the end-of-chapter writing
          prompt.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

